<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-447-317  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 447 317.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Sept 17 1990 n287 p54(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ATandamp;T: still on hold; less regulation could mean better, moreinexpensive service.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Thyfault, Mary E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>ATandamp;T asserts that the long-distance telephone market issufficiently competitive for the Federal Communications Commission(FCC) to loosen its regulatory limits on the company, which wouldenable it to provide better, innovative and individualizedservices plus lower prices.andP;  Competitors MCI Communications Corpand US Sprint Communications Co among others argue for continuedregulation because ATandamp;T has a 70 percent market share.andP;  The FCChas been investigating the long distance service market and hastentatively concluded that the market is competitive and thatregulations governing ATandamp;T should be loosened.andP;  The competitorscontend that the communications giant still retains manyadvantages of the pre-divestiture era and that it could use manyof its regulated services to gain customers in competitiveunregulated markets.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (telecommunication policy).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     Government RegulationLong-Distance Telephone ServicesCompaniesCommunications IndustryCompetitionUnited States. Federal Communications Commission.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>